04933nam a22005415i 9780773588035DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735880357 a10.1515/97807735880352doi  a(DE-B1597)655536  a(OCoLC)828740287  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL86.D42 ǂb S28 2013eb 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a352.3309711 aSavoie, Donald J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhatever Happened to the Music Teacher? :bHow Government Decides and Why /cDonald J. Savoie. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPublic Administration without Romance -- tParliament: Try a Blank Piece of Paper -- tMinisters: Where Have All the Characters Gone? -- tThe Prime Minister: Give Me Time to Learn -- tThe Machinery: Running on Its Tracks -- tLet the Manager Manage So Long as It Squares with RPPs, DPRs, MAF, OCG, PCO, TBS, OAG, OLA, IBP, PSC, ATIP, CIEC, OPSICC, DAGs, QFR and That It Does Not Create Problems for the Minister and Deputy Minister or Draw the Attention of the Prime Minister and His Adviser -- tProgram Evaluation: Turning a Crank That’s Not Attached to Anything -- tThe Public Service: The Ambivalent Institution -- tManagement with a Capital M Never Interested Me Very Much -- tYou Can Fudge Reports but You Cannot Fudge Rules -- tSo What Happened to the Music Teacher? -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThirty years ago, Anglo-American politicians set out to make the public sector look like the private sector. These reforms continue today, ultimately seeking to empower elected officials to shape policies and pushing public servants to manage operations in the same manner as their private-sector counterparts. In Whatever Happened to the Music Teacher?, Donald Savoie provides a nuanced account of how the Canadian federal government makes decisions. Savoie argues that the traditional role of public servants advising governments on policy has been turned on its head, and that evidence-based policy making is no longer valued as it once was. Policy making has become a matter of opinion, Google searches, focus groups, and public opinion surveys, where a well-connected lobbyist can provide any answers politicians wish to hear. As a result, public servants have lost their way and are uncertain about how they should assess management performance, how they should generate policy advice, how they should work with their political leaders, and how they should speak truth to political power - even within their own departments. Savoie demonstrates how recent management reforms in government have caused a steep rise in the overhead cost of government, as well as how the notion that public administration could be made to operate like the private sector has been misguided and costly to taxpayers. Abandoning "textbook" discussions of government and public service, Whatever Happened to the Music Teacher? Is a realistic portrayal of how policy decisions are made and how actors and institutions interact with one another and exposes the complexities, contradictions present in Canadian politics and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada -- Politics and government -- Decision making -- Textbooks. 0aPolitical planning -- Canada -- Decision making -- Textbooks. 0aPublic administration -- Canada -- Decision making -- Textbooks. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTi